Returning a boolean is actually better here because the caller can know whether a subscription was deleted.

I would define the service like this:

Service Interface

public interface FedexUnsubscriptionService {

    boolean processFedexUnsubscription(String customerId,
                                       String accountNumber);

}


---

Service Implementation

@Slf4j
@Service
@RequiredArgsConstructor
@Transactional
public class FedexUnsubscriptionServiceImpl
        implements FedexUnsubscriptionService {

    private final FedexSubscriptionRepository fedexSubscriptionRepository;

    @Override
    public boolean processFedexUnsubscription(String customerId,
                                              String accountNumber) {

        log.info(new LogBuilder()
                .withMessage("Processing FedEx unsubscription request")
                .withField("customerId", customerId)
                .withField("accountNumber", accountNumber)
                .toString());

        Optional<String> orphanSubscription =
                fedexSubscriptionRepository
                        .findSubscriptionIdWithoutAccounts(customerId);

        if (orphanSubscription.isEmpty()) {

            log.info(new LogBuilder()
                    .withMessage("No orphan subscription found")
                    .withField("customerId", customerId)
                    .toString());

            return false;
        }

        fedexSubscriptionRepository.deleteBySubscriptionId(
                orphanSubscription.get());

        log.info(new LogBuilder()
                .withMessage("Successfully deleted orphan subscription")
                .withField("customerId", customerId)
                .withField("subscriptionId", orphanSubscription.get())
                .toString());

        return true;
    }
}

Meaning of the return value

true → A subscription was found with no accounts and was deleted.

false → Nothing was deleted (either no orphan subscription existed or no matching customer data).


One improvement I'd make

Instead of:

deleteBySubscriptionId(subscriptionId);
return true;

change your repository to:

@Modifying
@Transactional
@Query("""
    DELETE FROM FedexSubscriptionEntity fs
    WHERE fs.subscriptionId = :subscriptionId
    """)
int deleteBySubscriptionId(@Param("subscriptionId") String subscriptionId);

Then in the service:

int deletedRows =
        fedexSubscriptionRepository.deleteBySubscriptionId(
                orphanSubscription.get());

return deletedRows > 0;

This way you're returning the actual result of the delete operation rather than assuming it succeeded. It's a bit more robust and is a pattern often used in enterprise applications.